[0m[49m[39m  173, 175[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  174, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 177[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  176, 178[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  177, 179[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Local knowledge graph storage and SPARQL/Gremlin query execution at each institution |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 178     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS AppSync** | Federation API layer; receives queries, orchestrates decomposition and assembly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS AppSync** | Client-facing federation API; receives queries and returns assembled results |
[0m[49m[39m  179, 181[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Query decomposition, schema translation (per-institution adapters), result assembly |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 182[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Ontology registry; stores shared concept mappings and schema alignment files |
[0m[49m[39m  181, 183[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Source catalog; tracks participating institutions, their capabilities, and sharing policies |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 182     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS PrivateLink** | Secure cross-account connectivity between federation layer and institutional Neptune clusters |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS PrivateLink** | Secure cross-account connectivity between federation layer and institutional API Gateways |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | IAM-authenticated entry point at each institution, fronting the query adapter Lambda |
[0m[49m[39m  183, 186[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Organizations** | Multi-account governance and cross-account role management |
[0m[49m[39m  184, 187[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Query latency metrics, error rates, federation health monitoring |
[0m[49m[39m  185, 188[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS CloudTrail** | Audit trail for all federated queries and access decisions |
[0m[49m[39m  186, 189[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for Neptune, S3, and DynamoDB across accounts |
[0m[49m[39m  187, 190[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  188, 191[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  189, 192[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  190, 193[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  191, 194[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 195[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Register a source in the federation catalog.** Before an institution can participate in federated queries, it must register itself in the source catalog. This registration declares what types of knowledge the institution holds (drug interactions, treatment protocols, genomic associations), what ontology standards it aligns to, what sharing policies it enforces, and how to reach its query endpoint. Think of this as the institution raising its hand and saying "I have knowledge about these topics, and here's how to ask me about them." Without this step, the federation layer has no idea which sources to contact for a given query. The catalog is the routing table for the entire network.
[0m[49m[39m  193, 196[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  194, 197[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  195, 198[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION register_source(institution_id, capabilities, endpoint_config, sharing_policy):
[0m[49m[39m  196, 199[0m:[39m[49m     // Build the catalog entry that tells the federation layer everything it needs
[0m[49m[39m  197, 200[0m:[39m[49m     // to route queries to this institution and respect its governance rules.
[0m[49m[39m  198, 201[0m:[39m[49m     catalog_entry = {
[0m[49m[39m  199, 202[0m:[39m[49m         institution_id:   institution_id,          // unique identifier (e.g., "boston-medical-center")
[0m[49m[39m  200, 203[0m:[39m[49m         capabilities:     capabilities,            // list of knowledge domains this source covers
[0m[49m[39m  201, 204[0m:[39m[49m                                                    // e.g., ["drug_interactions", "genomic_associations", "treatment_protocols"]
[0m[49m[39m  202, 205[0m:[39m[49m         ontology_version: "SNOMED-CT-2025-03",     // which version of the shared ontology this source aligns to
[0m[49m[39m  203, 206[0m:[39m[49m         endpoint:         endpoint_config,         // PrivateLink endpoint ARN and connection details
[0m[49m[39m  204, 207[0m:[39m[49m         sharing_policy:   sharing_policy,          // rules governing what can be shared and with whom
[0m[49m[39m  205, 208[0m:[39m[49m                                                    // e.g., { "drug_interactions": "public", "patient_derived": "research_only" }
[0m[49m[39m  206, 209[0m:[39m[49m         registered_at:    current UTC timestamp,
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 207     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         status:           "active"                 // can be set to "suspended" to temporarily disable
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status:           "active",                // can be set to "suspended" to temporarily disable
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         health: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             consecutive_failures: 0,               // circuit breaker counter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             last_success:         null,            // timestamp of last successful query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             last_failure:         null             // timestamp of last failed query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  208, 216[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  209, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  210, 218[0m:[39m[49m     // Write to the source catalog (DynamoDB table).
[0m[49m[39m  211, 219[0m:[39m[49m     // The federation layer reads this catalog at query time to determine routing.
[0m[49m[39m  212, 220[0m:[39m[49m     write catalog_entry to DynamoDB table "federation-source-catalog"
[0m[49m[39m  213, 221[0m:[39m[49m         with key = institution_id
[0m[49m[39m  214, 222[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 223[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN catalog_entry
[0m[49m[39m  216, 224[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  217, 225[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 226[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Load and version ontology mappings.** Each institution models clinical concepts differently. One might represent "Type 2 Diabetes" as a SNOMED code (44054006). Another might use an ICD-10 code (E11). A third might use a local identifier. The ontology mapping layer translates between these representations so that a federated query for "treatments for Type 2 Diabetes" can be understood by every source, regardless of their local coding system. These mappings are stored in S3, versioned, and loaded by the query translation Lambdas. Maintaining these mappings is ongoing work. Every time a source updates their local schema or a new ontology version is released, the mappings need updating. Skip this step and federated queries will miss results because they're asking in the wrong "language" for each source.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 227[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  220, 228[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  221, 229[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION load_ontology_mapping(source_institution_id, mapping_version):
[0m[49m[39m  222, 230[0m:[39m[49m     // Fetch the mapping file for this institution from the ontology registry in S3.
[0m[49m[39m  223, 231[0m:[39m[49m     // Each institution has its own mapping file that translates between the
[0m[49m[39m  224, 232[0m:[39m[49m     // federated schema (shared vocabulary) and their local schema.
[0m[49m[39m  225, 233[0m:[39m[49m     mapping_key = "ontology-mappings/{source_institution_id}/v{mapping_version}.json"
[0m[49m[39m  226, 234[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 235[0m:[39m[49m     mapping_file = read from S3 bucket "federation-ontology-registry" at key mapping_key
[0m[49m[39m  228, 236[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  229, 237[0m:[39m[49m     // The mapping file contains bidirectional translations:
[0m[49m[39m  230, 238[0m:[39m[49m     // - federated_to_local: how to translate a federated concept into this source's local representation
[0m[49m[39m  231, 239[0m:[39m[49m     // - local_to_federated: how to translate this source's results back into federated vocabulary
[0m[49m[39m  232, 240[0m:[39m[49m     // Example entry:
[0m[49m[39m  233, 241[0m:[39m[49m     // {
[0m[49m[39m  234, 242[0m:[39m[49m     //   "concept": "type_2_diabetes",
[0m[49m[39m  235, 243[0m:[39m[49m     //   "federated_code": "SNOMED:44054006",
[0m[49m[39m  236, 244[0m:[39m[49m     //   "local_code": "ICD10:E11",
[0m[49m[39m  237, 245[0m:[39m[49m     //   "local_node_type": "Diagnosis",
[0m[49m[39m  238, 246[0m:[39m[49m     //   "local_property": "icd_code"
[0m[49m[39m  239, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // }
[0m[49m[39m  240, 248[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 249[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN parsed mapping_file
[0m[49m[39m  242, 250[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  243, 251[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 244     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Decompose a federated query.** When a clinician asks a question like "what drug interactions are known for Metformin in patients with renal impairment?", the federation layer needs to figure out which sources might have relevant answers and how to ask each one. This is query decomposition. The decomposer consults the source catalog to identify sources with relevant capabilities, loads the ontology mapping for each source, and rewrites the query into each source's local query language. It then dispatches all sub-queries in parallel. This is the heart of the federation engine. Get it wrong and you either miss relevant sources (incomplete results) or flood irrelevant sources with queries they can't answer (wasted latency and cost).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Decompose a federated query.** When a clinician asks a question like "what drug interactions are known for Metformin in patients with renal impairment?", the federation layer needs to figure out which sources might have relevant answers and how to ask each one. This is query decomposition. The decomposer consults the source catalog to identify sources with relevant capabilities, loads the ontology mapping for each source, and rewrites the query into each source's local query language. It then dispatches all sub-queries in parallel with per-source timeouts and circuit breaker protection. This is the heart of the federation engine. Get it wrong and you either miss relevant sources (incomplete results) or flood irrelevant sources with queries they can't answer (wasted latency and cost).
[0m[49m[39m  245, 253[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  246, 254[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  247, 255[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION decompose_and_route(federated_query, requester_context):
[0m[49m[39m  248, 256[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse the incoming federated query to understand what's being asked.
[0m[49m[39m  249, 257[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract the knowledge domains involved (e.g., "drug_interactions", "renal")
[0m[49m[39m  250, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // and the clinical concepts referenced (e.g., "Metformin", "renal_impairment").
[0m[49m[39m  251, 259[0m:[39m[49m     query_domains  = extract_domains(federated_query)
[0m[49m[39m  252, 260[0m:[39m[49m     query_concepts = extract_concepts(federated_query)
[0m[49m[39m  253, 261[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  254, 262[0m:[39m[49m     // Look up which sources have relevant capabilities.
[0m[49m[39m  255, 263[0m:[39m[49m     // A source registered with capability "drug_interactions" is a candidate
[0m[49m[39m  256, 264[0m:[39m[49m     // for a query about drug interactions. Sources without that capability are skipped.
[0m[49m[39m  257, 265[0m:[39m[49m     candidate_sources = query DynamoDB "federation-source-catalog"
[0m[49m[39m  258, 266[0m:[39m[49m         WHERE capabilities OVERLAPS query_domains
[0m[49m[39m  259, 267[0m:[39m[49m         AND status = "active"
[0m[49m[39m  260, 268[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 261     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // For each candidate source, check sharing policy against requester context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Circuit breaker check: skip sources that have failed repeatedly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If a source has timed out or errored on 3+ consecutive queries within
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the last 5 minutes, mark it as "degraded" and skip it until a health
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // check succeeds. This prevents one slow source from dragging down every query.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     healthy_candidates = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each source in candidate_sources:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF source.health.consecutive_failures >= 3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m            AND (now - source.health.last_failure) < 5 minutes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Source is in circuit-breaker open state. Skip it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             log warning "Skipping degraded source: {source.institution_id}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append source to healthy_candidates
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each healthy candidate, check sharing policy against requester context.
[0m[49m[39m  262, 284[0m:[39m[49m     // The requester_context includes: who is asking, from which institution,
[0m[49m[39m  263, 285[0m:[39m[49m     // for what purpose (clinical care, research, quality improvement).
[0m[49m[39m  264, 286[0m:[39m[49m     authorized_sources = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 265     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     FOR each source in candidate_sources:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each source in healthy_candidates:
[0m[49m[39m  266, 288[0m:[39m[49m         IF evaluate_sharing_policy(source.sharing_policy, requester_context):
[0m[49m[39m  267, 289[0m:[39m[49m             append source to authorized_sources
[0m[49m[39m  268, 290[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  269, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // For each authorized source, translate the federated query into the local schema.
[0m[49m[39m  270, 292[0m:[39m[49m     sub_queries = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  271, 293[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each source in authorized_sources:
[0m[49m[39m  272, 294[0m:[39m[49m         mapping = load_ontology_mapping(source.institution_id, source.ontology_version)
[0m[49m[39m  273, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 296[0m:[39m[49m         // Rewrite the query using this source's local vocabulary.
[0m[49m[39m  275, 297[0m:[39m[49m         // "Metformin" might be represented as RxNorm:6809 in one source
[0m[49m[39m  276, 298[0m:[39m[49m         // and as a node with property drug_name="metformin" in another.
[0m[49m[39m  277, 299[0m:[39m[49m         local_query = translate_query(federated_query, mapping)
[0m[49m[39m  278, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  279, 301[0m:[39m[49m         append to sub_queries: {
[0m[49m[39m  280, 302[0m:[39m[49m             source:      source,
[0m[49m[39m  281, 303[0m:[39m[49m             local_query: local_query,
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 282     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             endpoint:    source.endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             endpoint:    source.endpoint,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timeout:     source.timeout OR default 3 seconds  // per-source timeout
[0m[49m[39m  283, 306[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  284, 307[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  285, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // Dispatch all sub-queries in parallel. Don't wait for one to finish
[0m[49m[39m  286, 309[0m:[39m[49m     // before sending the next. Network latency is the bottleneck in federation.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 287     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     results = execute_all_in_parallel(sub_queries)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Per-source timeout: if a source doesn't respond within its configured
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // timeout, mark it as timed_out but don't block the overall response.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     timed_out = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each sub_query in sub_queries (IN PARALLEL):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         TRY with timeout = sub_query.timeout:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             response = invoke sub_query.endpoint with sub_query.local_query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append response to results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Reset circuit breaker on success
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             update source.health: consecutive_failures = 0, last_success = now
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ON TIMEOUT:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append sub_query.source.institution_id to timed_out
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Increment circuit breaker counter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             update source.health: consecutive_failures += 1, last_failure = now
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ON ERROR:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append sub_query.source.institution_id to timed_out
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             update source.health: consecutive_failures += 1, last_failure = now
[0m[49m[39m  288, 327[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 289     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     RETURN results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN { results: results, timed_out: timed_out }
[0m[49m[39m  290, 329[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  291, 330[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  292, 331[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Execute a local query with access control.** Each institution's query adapter receives a translated query from the federation layer, validates the requester's authorization, executes the query against the local Neptune graph, and returns results with provenance metadata attached. This is where institutional governance is enforced. The adapter can filter results based on fine-grained policies: "share drug interaction data with any federation member, but restrict patient-derived treatment outcomes to approved research collaborators only." The adapter also attaches provenance to every result: where it came from, what evidence supports it, and when it was last validated. Skip the access control and you've built a data breach. Skip the provenance and clinicians can't assess the trustworthiness of results.
[0m[49m[39m  293, 332[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  294, 333[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  295, 334[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION execute_local_query(translated_query, requester_context, local_neptune_endpoint):
[0m[49m[39m  296, 335[0m:[39m[49m     // Validate that the requester is authorized for this specific query.
[0m[49m[39m  297, 336[0m:[39m[49m     // This is a second check (the federation layer already checked sharing policy),
[0m[49m[39m  298, 337[0m:[39m[49m     // but defense in depth matters when PHI-derived knowledge is involved.
[0m[49m[39m  299, 338[0m:[39m[49m     IF NOT validate_authorization(requester_context, translated_query):
[0m[49m[39m  300, 339[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN { status: "denied", reason: "insufficient_authorization" }
[0m[49m[39m  301, 340[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  302, 341[0m:[39m[49m     // Execute the translated query against the local Neptune cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  303, 342[0m:[39m[49m     // This is a standard SPARQL or Gremlin query at this point.
[0m[49m[39m  304, 343[0m:[39m[49m     raw_results = execute query translated_query against local_neptune_endpoint
[0m[49m[39m  305, 344[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  306, 345[0m:[39m[49m     // Attach provenance metadata to each result.
[0m[49m[39m  307, 346[0m:[39m[49m     // Clinicians need to know: where did this knowledge come from?
[0m[49m[39m  308, 347[0m:[39m[49m     // What's the evidence basis? How current is it?
[0m[49m[39m  309, 348[0m:[39m[49m     enriched_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  310, 349[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each result in raw_results:
[0m[49m[39m  311, 350[0m:[39m[49m         append to enriched_results: {
[0m[49m[39m  312, 351[0m:[39m[49m             data:       result,
[0m[49m[39m  313, 352[0m:[39m[49m             provenance: {
[0m[49m[39m  314, 353[0m:[39m[49m                 source_institution: local_institution_id,
[0m[49m[39m  315, 354[0m:[39m[49m                 evidence_level:     result.evidence_level OR "ungraded",
[0m[49m[39m  316, 355[0m:[39m[49m                 last_validated:     result.last_validated OR "unknown",
[0m[49m[39m  317, 356[0m:[39m[49m                 derivation_method:  result.derivation_method OR "curated"
[0m[49m[39m  318, 357[0m:[39m[49m                                     // "curated" = human-reviewed
[0m[49m[39m  319, 358[0m:[39m[49m                                     // "nlp_extracted" = machine-extracted from literature
[0m[49m[39m  320, 359[0m:[39m[49m                                     // "claims_derived" = inferred from claims data
[0m[49m[39m  321, 360[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  322, 361[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  323, 362[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  324, 363[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply result-level filtering based on sharing policy.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 364[0m:[39m[49m     // Some results might be shareable while others from the same query are restricted.
[0m[49m[39m  326, 365[0m:[39m[49m     filtered_results = apply_result_level_policy(enriched_results, requester_context)
[0m[49m[39m  327, 366[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 367[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN filtered_results
[0m[49m[39m  329, 368[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  330, 369[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  331, 370[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Assemble and deduplicate federated results.** Results stream back from multiple sources. The assembler's job is to merge them into a coherent, deduplicated response. This is harder than it sounds. Two sources might report the same drug interaction with different severity ratings. Three sources might report the same treatment with different evidence levels. The assembler needs strategies for conflict resolution: highest evidence level wins? Most recent validation date wins? Majority vote? The right strategy depends on the use case. For clinical decision support, you probably want to surface all perspectives with their provenance rather than silently picking a winner. For automated alerting, you need a deterministic resolution. This step also handles ranking: results with stronger evidence and more recent validation appear first.
[0m[49m[39m  332, 371[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 372[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  334, 373[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION assemble_results(partial_results_from_all_sources):
[0m[49m[39m  335, 374[0m:[39m[49m     // Flatten all results into a single list with their provenance intact.
[0m[49m[39m  336, 375[0m:[39m[49m     all_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  337, 376[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each source_response in partial_results_from_all_sources:
[0m[49m[39m  338, 377[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each result in source_response:
[0m[49m[39m  339, 378[0m:[39m[49m             append result to all_results
[0m[49m[39m  340, 379[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  341, 380[0m:[39m[49m     // Deduplicate: identify results that refer to the same underlying knowledge.
[0m[49m[39m  342, 381[0m:[39m[49m     // Two sources might both report "Metformin interacts with Contrast Dye"
[0m[49m[39m  343, 382[0m:[39m[49m     // but with different severity ratings or evidence levels.
[0m[49m[39m  344, 383[0m:[39m[49m     // Group by canonical concept (using the federated ontology codes).
[0m[49m[39m  345, 384[0m:[39m[49m     grouped = group all_results by canonical_concept_key(result.data)
[0m[49m[39m  346, 385[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  347, 386[0m:[39m[49m     // For each group of duplicates, merge into a single federated result.
[0m[49m[39m  348, 387[0m:[39m[49m     merged_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  349, 388[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each concept_key, group in grouped:
[0m[49m[39m  350, 389[0m:[39m[49m         IF length(group) == 1:
[0m[49m[39m  351, 390[0m:[39m[49m             // Only one source reported this. Use it directly.
[0m[49m[39m  352, 391[0m:[39m[49m             append group[0] to merged_results
[0m[49m[39m  353, 392[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  354, 393[0m:[39m[49m             // Multiple sources reported this. Merge with conflict resolution.
[0m[49m[39m  355, 394[0m:[39m[49m             merged = {
[0m[49m[39m  356, 395[0m:[39m[49m                 data:        consensus_or_highest_evidence(group),
[0m[49m[39m  357, 396[0m:[39m[49m                 provenance:  collect all provenance records from group,
[0m[49m[39m  358, 397[0m:[39m[49m                 consensus:   calculate_agreement_score(group),
[0m[49m[39m  359, 398[0m:[39m[49m                              // 1.0 = all sources agree; 0.5 = split opinion
[0m[49m[39m  360, 399[0m:[39m[49m                 source_count: length(group)
[0m[49m[39m  361, 400[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  362, 401[0m:[39m[49m             append merged to merged_results
[0m[49m[39m  363, 402[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  364, 403[0m:[39m[49m     // Rank results: higher evidence level and more sources = higher rank.
[0m[49m[39m  365, 404[0m:[39m[49m     sort merged_results by (evidence_level DESC, source_count DESC, last_validated DESC)
[0m[49m[39m  366, 405[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  367, 406[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN merged_results
[0m[49m[39m  368, 407[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  369, 408[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  370, 409[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter13.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
